<br>
Look at it this way.<br>
<br>
You grew up with another person. That person lied, cheated whatever. Now you both are grown and that person has children of their own. Those children are sweet wellbehaved children, do you still hold against them the mistakes their parent has made? Their father once broke your favorite toy because you did not give it to him when he demanded it. Do you hold their child responsible for that broken toy? I wouldn't, because that child is not their parent.<br>
<br>
Even if there was an Adam and Eve , why should we be held responsible for their actions and deeds? It seems very vengeful and hateful for a God that is supposidely loving and kind. <br>
<br>
Which brings to mind another question. Do you (anyone) feel that man in naturally ammoral, or even evil? Atheists, do you think man is naturally good? neutrual? evil? <br>
<br>
Is a child damned from the start because of their inhereted sinful nature? Or is that damnation bestowed upon them when they turn 18 and are therefore an adult? At what point does the innocence of a child become the evilness of the adult?<br>
<br>
